diff --git a/test/fuzzer/pedro/restart_current_time.test b/test/fuzzer/pedro/restart_current_time.test
index b86c2aee3863..5a3b4de8dbe7 100644
--- a/test/fuzzer/pedro/restart_current_time.test
+++ b/test/fuzzer/pedro/restart_current_time.test
@@ -4,13 +4,7 @@
 
 load __TEST_DIR__/restart_current_time.db
 
-statement ok
+statement error
 CREATE TABLE t0 (c1 INT, CHECK (CURRENT_TIME >= TIME '00:00:00'));
-
-restart
-
-statement ok
-INSERT INTO t0(c1) VALUES (0);
-
-statement ok
-DROP TABLE t0;
+----
+Table does not contain column CURRENT_TIME
diff --git a/test/sql/parser/test_value_functions.test b/test/sql/parser/test_value_functions.test
new file mode 100644
index 000000000000..6d3f44c2d22a
--- /dev/null
+++ b/test/sql/parser/test_value_functions.test
@@ -0,0 +1,42 @@
+# name: test/sql/parser/test_value_functions.test
+# description: Test SQL value functions
+# group: [parser]
+
+statement ok
+PRAGMA enable_verification
+
+# by default these columns can be used as per usual
+query I
+SELECT user FROM (VALUES ('hello world')) t(user)
+----
+hello world
+
+# if the column is not found they are turned into the SQL value function
+query I
+SELECT user
+----
+duckdb
+
+query I
+SELECT UsEr
+----
+duckdb
+
+# run all SQL value functions
+# need to run without verification since CURRENT_TIME etc break verification
+statement ok
+PRAGMA disable_verification
+
+require icu
+
+foreach value_function current_catalog current_date current_schema current_role current_time current_timestamp current_user localtime localtimestamp session_user user
+
+statement ok
+SELECT ${value_function}
+
+endloop
+
+statement error
+SELECT useRrr
+----
+useRrr
problem_statement:
Handle Postgres' value functions (LOCALTIME, CURRENT_TIME, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, etc) less confusingly
Postgres has a large number of "special columns" that are implicitly converted into functions when used - these are called "value functions" in the grammar. We have inherited these from their parser. For example:

```sql
SELECT user;
┌─────────┐
│ user()  │
│ varchar │
├─────────┤
│ duckdb  │
└─────────┘
SELECT localtime;
┌─────────────────────┐
│ current_localtime() │
│        time         │
├─────────────────────┤
│ 21:38:50.948        │
└─────────────────────┘
SELECT current_catalog;
┌───────────────────┐
│ current_catalog() │
│      varchar      │
├───────────────────┤
│ memory            │
└───────────────────┘
```

These can cause confusion if used as a regular column in a table - since, instead of accessing the column (as expected) the function is called instead. For example:

```sql
create table users("user" varchar);
insert into users values ('my user account');
select user from users;
┌─────────┐
│ user()  │
│ varchar │
├─────────┤
│ duckdb  │
└─────────┘
```

We should handle this differently. Rather than handling this in the parser, we should handle these during binding. Similar to `rowid` - we should **only** convert this to a function if it is non-ambiguous (i.e. if there is no column of the same name).

If there is a column of the same name, we should either (1) just refer to this column (my preference), or (2) throw an ambiguity exception and ask the user to quote the column.

The complete list of these value functions is as follows:

```
CURRENT_DATE
CURRENT_TIME
CURRENT_TIMESTAMP
LOCALTIME
LOCALTIMESTAMP
CURRENT_ROLE
CURRENT_USER
SESSION_USER
USER
CURRENT_CATALOG
CURRENT_SCHEMA
```
